    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-01-04T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-01-04T13:00:00-05:00" n="258"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/1–450: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bruce</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-01-04T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 4, 1950—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>46. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss>s 5016, December 30, and 8, January
                    3. We took up with Couve de Murville<note n="1" xml:id="d258fn1">Maurice Couve
                        de Murville, Director General of Political Affairs, French Ministry for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> today Department’s proposal for consultations with
                    French, British and Belgian Governments on colonial problems. He said he would
                    discuss it immediately with Schuman<note n="2" xml:id="d258fn2">Robert Schuman,
                        French Minister of Foreign Affairs.</note> but for his part he regarded it
                    as a very happy and timely initiative and one in which the French Government
                    would be glad to cooperate. He deprecated the differences which had arisen in
                    New York and attached great importance to trying to iron them out before next
                    General Assembly.</p>
                <p>On specific points raised in second paragraph <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 5016 he said French had no intention of taking any public
                    position. Without commenting directly on request that no “final conclusions” be
                    reached he did say that French intend to proceed with consultations with British
                    and Belgians.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 46, repeated London 15, Brussels 6.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
